 #In Q1 we learn that to name each column name, we have to -c() and name each column in order. We also learn that R is case sentative and we should always put the name the way we see it whenever we refernece it.

 Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Gender <- factor(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Gender, levels = c(1,2), labels = c('Male','Female'))
 
 Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Satisfactory <- factor(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Satisfactory, levels = c(1,2,3,4), labels = c('Very Satisfied','Moderately Satisfied','A Little Dissatisfied','Very Dissatisfied'))
 
 Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Job Characteristics` <- factor(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Job Characteristics`, levels = c(1,2,3,4,5), labels = c('High Income','No Danger of Being Fired','Flexible Hours','Opportunities for Advancement','Enjoying the Work'))
 
 Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Decision Making` <- factor(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Decision Making`, levels = c(1,2,3,4), labels = c('Always','Much of the Time','Sometimes','Never'))

 Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Budgetary Decisions`<- factor(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Budgetary Decisions`, levels = c(1,2), labels = c('Yes','No'))
 
 Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Happiness <- factor(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Happiness, levels = c(1,2,3,4), labels = c('Very Proud','Somewhat Proud','Indifferent','Not At All Proud'))
 
 Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Resigning <- factor(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Resigning, levels = c(1,2,3,4,5), labels = c('Very Likely','Likely','Not Sure','Unlikely','Very Unlikely'))
 
 Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Relations <- factor(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Relations, levels = c(1,2,3,4,5), labels = c('Very Good','Good','So So','Bad','Very Bad'))
 
 Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Likely to be promoted` <- factor(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Likely to be promoted`, levels = c(1,2,3,4,5), labels = c('Very Likely','Likely','Not Sure','Unlikely','Very Unlikely'))

 # In Q3 We learn that we have an option to make the column a factor or we can name each factor inside the colunm. We also learn that numbers that are real data like 'Age' and 'Years worked' can't be factors.

#Q4
 hist(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Age, col = "red", main = "Age of Employees", xlab = "Age", ylab = "Number of People")

 plot(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Gender,col = "blue", main = "Gender of Employees", xlab = "Gender")

 plot(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Satisfactory, col = "brown", main = "Satisfaction of Employees", xlab ="Satisfaction", cex.names = 0.7)

 plot(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Job Characteristics`, col = "purple", main = "Job Characteristics of Employees", xlab ="Job Characteristics", cex.names = .5)

 hist(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Years Worked`, col = "red", main = "Years Employees Worked", xlab ="Years Worked", ylab = "Number of Employees")

 plot(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Likely to be promoted`, col = "green", main = "Employees that are Likely to be Promoted", xlab ="How Likely to be Promoted", cex.names = .6)

 plot(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Decision Making`, col = "black", main = "Employees Decision Making", xlab ="How Many Times Employees Make Decisions", cex.names = .7)

 plot(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Budgetary Decisions`, col = "grey", main = "Employees Budgetary Decisions", xlab ="How Many Times Employees Make Budgetary Decisions")

 plot(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Happiness, col = "blue", main = "How Happy are Employees", xlab ="Employees Happiness", cex.names = .7)

 plot(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Resigning, col = "pink", main = "How Likely it is for an Employee to Resign", xlab ="Employee Resigning")

 plot(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Relations, col = "orange", main = "Employees Relationships with Each Other", xlab ="Employee Relationships with Coworkers")

 #We learned in Q4 that the best way to represent factors is by doing a bar chart. We also learn that integer data can be best represented by a histogram.
     
#Q5
 plot(Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$Age, col = "pink", main = "Age VS Years of Employees Worked", xlab = "Age", ylab = "Years Worked", Typical_Employee_Survey_Data$`Years Worked`,pch = 16)

 #We learned in Q5 that the best way that you can represent 'Age' and 'Years Worked ' is through a scatter plot.We also learned that we can fill in the default points that R gives us with the code pch = 16.
